            <div type="translation" source="bib:SrinivasaAiyar1941_01">
                <p>
                    Hail! Prosperity! In the 21st year of Kōvirājakēsaripanmar (King Rājakēśarivarman)―In this year, to the Mahādēva (Śiva) of the <foreign>graha</foreign> (?) (inner-shrine) of Tiruppūdiśvaram<note>Pūdi or Bhūti was a name of Vikramakēsari of the Irukkuvēḷ or Koḍumbāḷūr line of chieftains. Tiruppūdīśvaram may be the Mucukuṇḍeśvara temple and he might have got his name Pūdi from the name of the God of the place.</note> (temple) at Koḍumbāḷūr in the Uṟattūr Kūṟṟam (division), for a lamp (to burn) perpetually without fail .... .... .... .... .... .... .... (<foreign>naḍi</foreign>) (?) .... .... .... .... .... .... .... .... .... ....
                </p>
            </div>            
            
            <div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">                
                
                <p n="1">Prosperity! Fortune!</p>
                <p n="1-2">21st year of the king Rājakesarivarman.</p>
                <p n="2-7">
                    In this year, for the Mahādeva of the Tiruppūtīśvaram<note><hi rend="italic">Pace</hi> <bibl><ptr target="bib:SrinivasaAiyar1941_01"/></bibl>, this is probably the present-day Mūvarkōyil founded by Bhūti Vikramakesarin. See <ref target="DHARMA_INSKotumpalur00001"/>.</note> of Koṭumpāḷūr in the Uṟattūrkkūṟṟam
                    <gap reason="lost"/>
                    one perpetual lamp
                    <gap reason="lost"/>
                    without fail
                    <gap reason="lost"/>
                </p>
                
            </div>
            
